I can't not talk about the image, it's too glaring for me to ignore, both in a meta and in-universe sense.

In the meta sense, I assume that a part of it is to avoid having nudity in an article as well as not sexualizing the anomaly (this last bit I'm taking from the  bit) but I can't see why you couldn't just have no image at all. First of all, if a scientific document had to have drawings rather than photographs, the drawings would have to be detailed and professional and, no offence, your drawing isn't up to par. As for the sexualization in the meta sense, assuming this was a reasoning so feel free to correct me, it feels contradictory to give her large breasts, a skinny frame, and a modelling pose. I would expect the sketch to have a neutral stance rather than the cover of a fashion magazine. It would also have made more sense to not have her be conventionally attractive. As it is, it feels like she's being sexualized even if there isn't any actual nudity.

From the point of view in-universe, I honestly can't imagine why the Ethics Committee would not approve of pictures. If we assume that the articles are just the summary of the anomaly and that there are a lot more notes and experiments in the database (would make sense since a lot of articles have a ) and keeps them locked against their will, not to mention the experimentation itself. So nude photographs for the purpose of documentation seems par for the course.

It just takes me out of the story to see what looks like a sketch of someone's  OC in what is supposed to be a serious piece of fiction in a scientific setting.







